tion and passes all tests.\n\n### Question:\nYou are given a 0-indexed binary string target of length n. You have another binary string s of length n that is initially set to all zeros. You want to make s equal to target.\nIn one operation, you can pick an index i where 0 <= i < n and flip all bits in the inclusive range [i, n - 1]. Flip means changing '0' to '1' and '1' to '0'.\nReturn the minimum number of operations needed to make s equal to target.\n \nExample 1:\n\nInput: target = \"10111\"\nOutput: 3\nExplanation: Initially, s = \"00000\".\nChoose index i = 2: \"00000\" -> \"00111\"\nChoose index i = 0: \"00111\" -> \"11000\"\nChoose index i = 1: \"11000\" -> \"10111\"\nWe need at least 3 flip operations to form target.\n\nExample 2:\n\nInput: target = \"101\"\nOutput: 3\nExplanation: Initially, s = \"000\".\nChoose index i = 0: \"000\" -> \"111\"\nChoose index i = 1: \"111\" -> \"100\"\nChoose index i = 2: \"100\" -> \"101\"\nWe need at least 3 flip operations to form target.\n\nExample 3:\n\nInput: target = \"00000\"\nOutput: 0\nExplanation: We do not need any operations since the initial s already equals target.\n\n \nConstraints:\n\nn == target.length\n1 <= n <= 105\ntarget[i] is either '0' or '1'.\n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def minFlips(self, target: str) -> int:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nclass Solution:\n    def minFlips(self, target: str) -> int:\n        flips = 0\n        n = len(target)\n        i = 0\n        \n        # Skip leading zeros\n        while i < n and target[i] == '0':\n            i += 1\n        \n        # Count the number of flip transitions\n        while i < n:\n            if i == 0 or target[i] != target[i - 1]:\n                flips += 1\n            i += 1\n        \n        return flips\n```\n\n### Explanation:\n- We start by initializing a `flips` counter to 0 and an index `i` to 0.\n- We skip over any leading zeros in the target string since they do not require any flips to match the initial state of `s` which is all zeros.\n- We then iterate through the remaining characters in the target string.\n- We increment the `flips` counter each time we encounter a transition from '0' to '1' or from '1' to '0'. This is because each transition requires a flip operation to change the bits in the substring starting from that index to the end of the string.\n- Finally, we return the `flips` counter which represents the minimum number of flip operations needed to transform `s` into the target string.", "estimated_date": 1595721600000}